WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:00:00.506 --> 00:00:10.156 A:middle
[ Silence ]

00:00:10.656 --> 00:00:16.556 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Sal Soghoian: Welcome to
WWDC and especially welcome

00:00:16.556 --> 00:00:19.836 A:middle
to the first session
on automation today.

00:00:20.066 --> 00:00:20.806 A:middle
We have two.

00:00:20.806 --> 00:00:25.486 A:middle
This one's an overview of
all the new different things

00:00:25.486 --> 00:00:28.296 A:middle
in automation, and there's
a lot to talk about today.

00:00:29.206 --> 00:00:33.726 A:middle
I'll be joined in this
presentation by Chris Nebel.

00:00:33.726 --> 00:00:38.306 A:middle
He's the Senior Automation
Engineer and, when he comes back

00:00:38.306 --> 00:00:40.296 A:middle
from being wired up,
he'll stand over here

00:00:40.296 --> 00:00:42.096 A:middle
and do some of the demos.

00:00:42.416 --> 00:00:45.436 A:middle
But, like I said, we
have a lot to talk about.

00:00:45.986 --> 00:00:48.316 A:middle
There's been a lot of
work and a lot of changes,

00:00:48.316 --> 00:00:50.376 A:middle
and I think you're going to
enjoy some of these things.

00:00:50.376 --> 00:00:51.206 A:middle
So let's begin.

00:00:54.076 --> 00:00:56.676 A:middle
So what's new in the
world of automation?

00:00:56.956 --> 00:01:00.636 A:middle
Well, without actually just
bullet pointing the whole list,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:00:56.956 --> 00:01:00.636 A:middle
Well, without actually just
bullet pointing the whole list,

00:01:01.196 --> 00:01:05.465 A:middle
we're going to be talking about
Automator and AppleScript.

00:01:06.066 --> 00:01:09.376 A:middle
Especially we're going to
introduce some new features.

00:01:09.716 --> 00:01:11.086 A:middle
They're very powerful.

00:01:11.086 --> 00:01:12.426 A:middle
Some of them are
pretty dramatic.

00:01:12.426 --> 00:01:14.616 A:middle
I think you're going to find

00:01:14.756 --> 00:01:18.126 A:middle
that they become your
favorite things to work with.

00:01:19.456 --> 00:01:23.806 A:middle
And we're going to look at
multiple computer file access.

00:01:24.786 --> 00:01:29.306 A:middle
We'll be looking at some
security transparency issues,

00:01:29.886 --> 00:01:35.056 A:middle
some new OS X integration
that we've created,

00:01:35.056 --> 00:01:38.186 A:middle
and getting your
computer to pay attention

00:01:38.186 --> 00:01:39.886 A:middle
to what you want
it to do for you.

00:01:40.766 --> 00:01:43.906 A:middle
So those are my mystery
topics here, and we'll begin

00:01:43.906 --> 00:01:48.296 A:middle
with the simplest
multicomputer file integration

00:01:48.296 --> 00:01:50.466 A:middle
which is iCloud support,

00:01:51.206 --> 00:01:53.236 A:middle
specifically documents
in the Cloud.

00:01:53.896 --> 00:01:56.366 A:middle
Now, you're all familiar
with how this works.

00:01:56.366 --> 00:01:58.676 A:middle
You can create a
document on one computer.

00:01:58.676 --> 00:02:02.376 A:middle
You store it in the Cloud, and
it automatically gets pushed

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:58.676 --> 00:02:02.376 A:middle
You store it in the Cloud, and
it automatically gets pushed

00:02:02.756 --> 00:02:06.386 A:middle
to another computer using
your same iCloud account.

00:02:07.186 --> 00:02:10.116 A:middle
Now, through the magic of
automation and iCloud support,

00:02:10.406 --> 00:02:16.406 A:middle
we've incorporated this into the
AppleScript Editor, and it works

00:02:16.546 --> 00:02:18.526 A:middle
in the same way that
you're used to working

00:02:18.526 --> 00:02:19.906 A:middle
with other applications

00:02:19.906 --> 00:02:22.136 A:middle
that have document
in the Cloud support.

00:02:22.136 --> 00:02:25.476 A:middle
You can drag your favorite
scripts and applets right

00:02:25.476 --> 00:02:28.256 A:middle
into the iCloud window.

00:02:28.506 --> 00:02:31.576 A:middle
They'll automatically load
and go up to the server.

00:02:31.766 --> 00:02:36.596 A:middle
And then you can search based
upon tags that you've applied:

00:02:37.106 --> 00:02:39.676 A:middle
key words, names,
those kind of things.

00:02:40.366 --> 00:02:43.036 A:middle
And, in addition, you can
use some of the resources

00:02:43.166 --> 00:02:48.886 A:middle
of the iCloud viewer to sort
and organize your scripts

00:02:49.226 --> 00:02:53.036 A:middle
and to be able to use the
shared menu to send them,

00:02:53.926 --> 00:02:58.586 A:middle
share them over iDrop,
AirDrop or iMessage

00:02:58.586 --> 00:02:59.516 A:middle
or something like that.

00:02:59.516 --> 00:03:04.456 A:middle
So here's an AirDrop example
where you're taking something

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:59.516 --> 00:03:04.456 A:middle
So here's an AirDrop example
where you're taking something

00:03:04.456 --> 00:03:06.616 A:middle
from your Cloud and
you're sharing it across.

00:03:06.976 --> 00:03:07.486 A:middle
Hello there.

00:03:08.026 --> 00:03:12.456 A:middle
And we've incorporated this,
too, for Automator as well.

00:03:13.196 --> 00:03:16.106 A:middle
So not overly dramatic,
but you know what?

00:03:16.206 --> 00:03:20.616 A:middle
Being a script hoarder like
me, I'm actually starting

00:03:20.616 --> 00:03:23.146 A:middle
to like having one
place that I can go

00:03:23.146 --> 00:03:26.776 A:middle
to where I know I'll
find what I'm looking for

00:03:27.026 --> 00:03:28.686 A:middle
and copy it to the machine.

00:03:28.686 --> 00:03:30.226 A:middle
It's been very, very useful.

00:03:30.226 --> 00:03:32.286 A:middle
I think you're going
to find it useful too;

00:03:32.696 --> 00:03:36.536 A:middle
and you'll soon make
this just part

00:03:36.536 --> 00:03:39.736 A:middle
of your normal everyday
life with the editors.

00:03:41.196 --> 00:03:44.906 A:middle
Next we're going to look at
automation applets and security.

00:03:45.706 --> 00:03:48.236 A:middle
So the other day I get
an email from a friend

00:03:48.236 --> 00:03:49.606 A:middle
of mine, Trudy Anchover.

00:03:49.986 --> 00:03:50.796 A:middle
She's head of the --

00:03:50.926 --> 00:03:53.756 A:middle
she's Director for the
Bay Area Forest Scouts,

00:03:54.146 --> 00:03:55.906 A:middle
and she was at a
conference with me.

00:03:55.906 --> 00:03:58.886 A:middle
She saw me demonstrate
this little photo droplet.

00:03:59.446 --> 00:04:01.096 A:middle
And she asked me in
an email, you know,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:59.446 --> 00:04:01.096 A:middle
And she asked me in
an email, you know,

00:04:01.096 --> 00:04:02.806 A:middle
Can you share that with me?

00:04:02.806 --> 00:04:04.086 A:middle
It would really help me out.

00:04:04.316 --> 00:04:06.106 A:middle
So I didn't think
twice about it.

00:04:06.106 --> 00:04:09.406 A:middle
I just, you know, instantly
replied in an email message

00:04:09.406 --> 00:04:11.306 A:middle
to her, addressed
the email message.

00:04:11.726 --> 00:04:14.176 A:middle
I found the droplet, added it

00:04:14.176 --> 00:04:16.065 A:middle
to the email message,
and sent it to her.

00:04:16.065 --> 00:04:18.406 A:middle
I didn't think twice about this.

00:04:19.016 --> 00:04:20.565 A:middle
And then I send it to Trudy.

00:04:20.896 --> 00:04:26.786 A:middle
So when Trudy gets it on her
machine, she takes the droplet

00:04:26.786 --> 00:04:29.126 A:middle
from mail, drags
it to the desktop,

00:04:29.436 --> 00:04:31.586 A:middle
and is ready to use the droplet.

00:04:31.586 --> 00:04:34.646 A:middle
She selects an image and drags
it on top of the droplet.

00:04:35.236 --> 00:04:37.116 A:middle
And, instead of getting
processing,

00:04:37.116 --> 00:04:41.386 A:middle
she gets this dialog saying
that this droplet can't be run

00:04:41.386 --> 00:04:44.186 A:middle
because it's from an
unidentified developer

00:04:44.516 --> 00:04:47.576 A:middle
and that her settings
for security are set

00:04:47.576 --> 00:04:53.396 A:middle
to only use apple --
applets from the Apple Store

00:04:53.396 --> 00:04:55.436 A:middle
or from known developers.

00:04:55.946 --> 00:04:59.026 A:middle
Now, that's because,
in the Security

00:04:59.026 --> 00:05:04.166 A:middle
and Privacy Control Panel, she's
using a default setting which is

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:59.026 --> 00:05:04.166 A:middle
and Privacy Control Panel, she's
using a default setting which is

00:05:04.166 --> 00:05:07.036 A:middle
for Mac App Store and
identified developers.

00:05:07.486 --> 00:05:10.686 A:middle
Trudy's not a particularly
sophisticated user,

00:05:10.686 --> 00:05:13.356 A:middle
and so she doesn't know how
to bypass this or anything.

00:05:13.636 --> 00:05:16.046 A:middle
It just -- to her,
it's just broken.

00:05:16.426 --> 00:05:20.546 A:middle
And it's really my fault because
I forgot a very important thing

00:05:20.796 --> 00:05:24.196 A:middle
is that Automator and
AppleScript droplets

00:05:24.196 --> 00:05:26.806 A:middle
and applets are applications.

00:05:26.996 --> 00:05:30.016 A:middle
And, because they are
applications, they're subject

00:05:30.016 --> 00:05:32.406 A:middle
to the same level
of security scrutiny

00:05:32.406 --> 00:05:35.216 A:middle
as any other application
on the OS.

00:05:35.876 --> 00:05:38.526 A:middle
So, in order for them
to function correctly,

00:05:38.736 --> 00:05:43.556 A:middle
they really do need to be signed
to be Gatekeeper approved.

00:05:44.576 --> 00:05:47.386 A:middle
And you can try doing
that with the Terminal

00:05:47.386 --> 00:05:49.916 A:middle
and some magic commands,
if you like;

00:05:50.326 --> 00:05:54.646 A:middle
but now in Mavericks we are
introducing code signing support

00:05:54.646 --> 00:05:56.696 A:middle
built into our editing apps.

00:05:58.516 --> 00:06:01.546 A:middle
[ Applause ]

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:58.516 --> 00:06:01.546 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:06:02.046 --> 00:06:02.726 A:middle
Yeah. Really nice.

00:06:03.136 --> 00:06:06.766 A:middle
And it requires that you have,
you know, your developer ID,

00:06:06.926 --> 00:06:11.396 A:middle
which you do, and that you
have the Xcode installed

00:06:11.396 --> 00:06:12.956 A:middle
with the command line tools.

00:06:12.956 --> 00:06:16.146 A:middle
And, since we're
all developers here,

00:06:16.146 --> 00:06:17.776 A:middle
you're used to this concept

00:06:18.076 --> 00:06:21.296 A:middle
because you've been preparing
your apps for the Store anyway.

00:06:21.296 --> 00:06:24.076 A:middle
So you're used to
sending out signed copies.

00:06:24.396 --> 00:06:26.846 A:middle
And you already have
your developer ID

00:06:26.846 --> 00:06:29.496 A:middle
and certificates
installed into the keychain.

00:06:30.286 --> 00:06:33.586 A:middle
So, once you do, then you
can use this new feature.

00:06:33.586 --> 00:06:35.466 A:middle
And let me show you
what it looks like.

00:06:35.946 --> 00:06:37.666 A:middle
Here, in the AppleScript Editor,

00:06:38.196 --> 00:06:40.836 A:middle
I'm going to export
the droplet for Trudy.

00:06:41.266 --> 00:06:44.746 A:middle
And so I go to the File
menu and choose Export.

00:06:48.436 --> 00:06:51.156 A:middle
And when I do, I get
the dropdown sheet.

00:06:51.486 --> 00:06:56.416 A:middle
You'll notice that there's a
new pop-up menu at the bottom

00:06:56.416 --> 00:07:00.256 A:middle
of the Save sheet and
it says code sign.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:56.416 --> 00:07:00.256 A:middle
of the Save sheet and
it says code sign.

00:07:00.926 --> 00:07:03.296 A:middle
It's for code signing
and, by default,

00:07:03.296 --> 00:07:05.666 A:middle
it's set to don't code sign.

00:07:06.136 --> 00:07:08.766 A:middle
But if you do click
that pop-up menu,

00:07:09.016 --> 00:07:12.006 A:middle
all of your developer
identities that are installed

00:07:12.006 --> 00:07:14.426 A:middle
on that computer will
appear in this list.

00:07:14.946 --> 00:07:16.796 A:middle
It's just simply a
matter at that point

00:07:16.796 --> 00:07:19.076 A:middle
of choosing the identity
that you want

00:07:20.176 --> 00:07:23.646 A:middle
and then clicking the Save
button, and it will save a copy

00:07:23.646 --> 00:07:28.666 A:middle
of that droplet or applet
signed ready to deliver.

00:07:28.836 --> 00:07:31.376 A:middle
So, if I had done this for
Trudy, she wouldn't have had any

00:07:31.376 --> 00:07:33.876 A:middle
of the problems that
she came across.

00:07:35.106 --> 00:07:38.186 A:middle
For Automator, it's
a similar process.

00:07:38.186 --> 00:07:41.916 A:middle
So here I have a workflow
open in Automator.

00:07:41.916 --> 00:07:45.526 A:middle
This is one I use for
video editing quite a bit

00:07:46.106 --> 00:07:50.256 A:middle
and creating a compressed
video version from raw source.

00:07:50.776 --> 00:07:53.616 A:middle
And so, to do the same export,

00:07:53.616 --> 00:07:56.666 A:middle
I just go to the File
menu, choose Export.

00:07:57.506 --> 00:08:00.076 A:middle
I get the Save sheet
in Automator.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:57.506 --> 00:08:00.076 A:middle
I get the Save sheet
in Automator.

00:08:00.466 --> 00:08:01.836 A:middle
And at the bottom
of the Save sheet

00:08:01.836 --> 00:08:06.256 A:middle
in Automator is also a
code sign pop-up menu.

00:08:06.406 --> 00:08:10.126 A:middle
Again, I can select from that
menu the developer identity

00:08:10.126 --> 00:08:14.146 A:middle
that I'm looking for, pick
that, and then just click Save.

00:08:15.696 --> 00:08:19.196 A:middle
The applet will be saved
to wherever I indicated,

00:08:19.196 --> 00:08:21.616 A:middle
and it's signed and
ready to be distributed.

00:08:22.066 --> 00:08:24.196 A:middle
It's really that
easy to use these.

00:08:24.526 --> 00:08:28.256 A:middle
And, to show you that, I'm going
to turn to my friend Chris Nebel

00:08:28.706 --> 00:08:30.516 A:middle
and have Chris demonstrate.

00:08:31.216 --> 00:08:32.456 A:middle
Thank you.

00:08:33.515 --> 00:08:36.546 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:08:37.046 --> 00:08:37.566 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Chris Nebel: Thank you, Sal.

00:08:38.616 --> 00:08:40.916 A:middle
So let's take a look at how
Maverick makes it easier

00:08:40.916 --> 00:08:44.786 A:middle
to code sign your workflows,
applets, applications

00:08:45.126 --> 00:08:47.036 A:middle
so you can distribute
them to other users.

00:08:49.066 --> 00:08:52.366 A:middle
So I've got an applet
I've been working on here.

00:08:52.366 --> 00:08:53.896 A:middle
Notice getting this
out of iCloud.

00:08:54.586 --> 00:08:57.496 A:middle
It's working on another machine.

00:08:58.116 --> 00:09:00.206 A:middle
And I worked long and
hard on this applet.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:58.116 --> 00:09:00.206 A:middle
And I worked long and
hard on this applet.

00:09:00.206 --> 00:09:01.026 A:middle
I'm very proud of it.

00:09:01.196 --> 00:09:04.736 A:middle
I'm ready to send
it out to the world.

00:09:04.736 --> 00:09:07.916 A:middle
And, historically, what I
would do is I'd just, you know,

00:09:08.056 --> 00:09:10.486 A:middle
stick this in an email
message, send it off,

00:09:10.486 --> 00:09:12.316 A:middle
and the other person
would grab it from there.

00:09:12.686 --> 00:09:15.226 A:middle
So I have an applet
that simulates uploading

00:09:15.226 --> 00:09:18.326 A:middle
and downloading it, so it will
pop up in the Downloads folder.

00:09:18.916 --> 00:09:28.256 A:middle
And, if I open this now, I get
this dialog, and it's saying

00:09:28.256 --> 00:09:29.776 A:middle
that it can't open
this because it's

00:09:29.776 --> 00:09:30.956 A:middle
from an unidentified developer.

00:09:30.956 --> 00:09:34.096 A:middle
This is the default Gatekeeper
policy on everyone's system.

00:09:34.476 --> 00:09:38.046 A:middle
And OK here doesn't mean
"okay, go ahead and run it".

00:09:38.046 --> 00:09:39.706 A:middle
It means "okay, we're done".

00:09:39.706 --> 00:09:40.936 A:middle
There's nothing to do here.

00:09:40.936 --> 00:09:42.396 A:middle
This applet simply won't run.

00:09:43.436 --> 00:09:45.286 A:middle
And there is a workaround.

00:09:45.436 --> 00:09:47.996 A:middle
You can Control click on the
applet, open the long way

00:09:47.996 --> 00:09:49.276 A:middle
and you'll get a
different dialog.

00:09:49.276 --> 00:09:50.576 A:middle
But, for most users, as far

00:09:50.576 --> 00:09:52.716 A:middle
as they're concerned,
it's busted, right?

00:09:52.716 --> 00:09:58.076 A:middle
All they can really do
is throw it in the trash.

00:09:58.076 --> 00:10:01.346 A:middle
So how do I -- how do I make
life easier on my users here

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:09:58.076 --> 00:10:01.346 A:middle
So how do I -- how do I make
life easier on my users here

00:10:01.756 --> 00:10:03.926 A:middle
and not have them think
I'm a complete idiot

00:10:04.466 --> 00:10:05.876 A:middle
for sending them broken applets?

00:10:05.966 --> 00:10:09.676 A:middle
So, in Mountain Lion, we
added an Export command

00:10:09.676 --> 00:10:10.446 A:middle
to Script Editor.

00:10:10.446 --> 00:10:11.486 A:middle
The whole point of Export is

00:10:11.486 --> 00:10:13.376 A:middle
to save the script
for distribution.

00:10:13.806 --> 00:10:16.306 A:middle
In Mountain Lion, the main thing
that it did was it allows you

00:10:16.306 --> 00:10:19.806 A:middle
to save the script as run only,
taking that out of the Save

00:10:19.806 --> 00:10:24.236 A:middle
As dialog because who here has
accidentally saved a run-only

00:10:24.236 --> 00:10:26.506 A:middle
copy of their script
over their real one?

00:10:27.836 --> 00:10:29.016 A:middle
Uh-huh. I thought so.

00:10:29.116 --> 00:10:32.746 A:middle
So Export makes that
a little harder to do.

00:10:33.246 --> 00:10:38.766 A:middle
And now, in Mavericks,
here's run only

00:10:38.766 --> 00:10:40.666 A:middle
but here also is code sign.

00:10:41.906 --> 00:10:44.666 A:middle
So last year we showed you
how to do this in Terminal,

00:10:44.666 --> 00:10:45.766 A:middle
but now it's built right

00:10:45.766 --> 00:10:48.346 A:middle
into Script Editor
and into Automator.

00:10:49.066 --> 00:10:51.416 A:middle
And so, if I pick my --
my developer ID here,

00:10:52.206 --> 00:10:55.126 A:middle
I will save that to the desktop.

00:10:58.006 --> 00:10:59.286 A:middle
Yes, I want to allow this.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:11:00.596 --> 00:11:02.066 A:middle
So now I have my
code-signed version.

00:11:03.206 --> 00:11:07.366 A:middle
If I up and download
that and run it,

00:11:08.066 --> 00:11:09.086 A:middle
now I get a different dialog.

00:11:09.086 --> 00:11:11.476 A:middle
It says this is downloaded
from the Internet.

00:11:11.666 --> 00:11:14.126 A:middle
Gatekeeper is still not too
sure about this Internet thing.

00:11:14.336 --> 00:11:16.306 A:middle
Kind of new.

00:11:16.356 --> 00:11:18.996 A:middle
But now it's Cancel
and it's Open.

00:11:19.366 --> 00:11:24.086 A:middle
So, if I open, it goes
ahead and run -- and runs.

00:11:25.516 --> 00:11:27.836 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:11:28.336 --> 00:11:31.186 A:middle
So that is how -- so code
signing will make your

00:11:31.186 --> 00:11:31.846 A:middle
life easier.

00:11:31.846 --> 00:11:34.546 A:middle
Mavericks makes your life
easier code signing your applets

00:11:34.546 --> 00:11:35.456 A:middle
because it's now built right

00:11:35.456 --> 00:11:36.786 A:middle
into the editor you're
already using.

00:11:37.206 --> 00:11:40.386 A:middle
And it makes life easier on your
user because they don't have

00:11:40.446 --> 00:11:43.646 A:middle
to worry about long
hand waves of dealing

00:11:43.646 --> 00:11:44.896 A:middle
with nonsigned applets.

00:11:45.476 --> 00:11:47.036 A:middle
Sal, back to you.

00:11:47.736 --> 00:11:48.626 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Sal Soghoian: Thank you.

00:11:49.096 --> 00:11:51.356 A:middle
So it works with Automator

00:11:51.356 --> 00:11:53.626 A:middle
and AppleScript applets
and droplets.

00:11:53.906 --> 00:11:55.096 A:middle
They're applications.

00:11:55.376 --> 00:11:57.196 A:middle
You have to remember
that, if you're going

00:11:57.196 --> 00:12:00.106 A:middle
to distribute them now that
we have Gatekeeper, it --

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:11:57.196 --> 00:12:00.106 A:middle
to distribute them now that
we have Gatekeeper, it --

00:12:00.106 --> 00:12:02.196 A:middle
its default settings,
you might want

00:12:02.196 --> 00:12:03.946 A:middle
to just quickly do an export.

00:12:04.146 --> 00:12:06.356 A:middle
Code signing will even
save it as run only

00:12:06.356 --> 00:12:07.576 A:middle
if you like to as well.

00:12:07.756 --> 00:12:09.456 A:middle
And this has all
been integrated.

00:12:09.656 --> 00:12:11.866 A:middle
You can see it's a
very simple process.

00:12:12.596 --> 00:12:14.036 A:middle
Take advantage of it.

00:12:14.486 --> 00:12:16.556 A:middle
Next we're going to talk

00:12:16.556 --> 00:12:19.356 A:middle
about extending the
power of AppleScript.

00:12:20.336 --> 00:12:24.266 A:middle
And we're going to be doing that
with something that's brand new,

00:12:24.476 --> 00:12:27.876 A:middle
and it's called AppleScript
libraries.

00:12:30.486 --> 00:12:32.566 A:middle
Now, why libraries?

00:12:33.066 --> 00:12:36.066 A:middle
Well, I assume that
many of you are like me.

00:12:36.866 --> 00:12:41.656 A:middle
You're the kind of person
has hundreds and hundreds

00:12:42.336 --> 00:12:47.226 A:middle
of your favorite routines that
you've written over and over

00:12:47.226 --> 00:12:50.906 A:middle
and over for lots of different
situations and scenarios,

00:12:51.516 --> 00:12:54.926 A:middle
and you want to be able to
use those in multiple scripts.

00:12:54.926 --> 00:12:58.616 A:middle
So I have four or five things if
I have a script that's dealing

00:12:58.616 --> 00:13:00.716 A:middle
with text I'm going
to be pasting these

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:12:58.616 --> 00:13:00.716 A:middle
with text I'm going
to be pasting these

00:13:00.716 --> 00:13:03.056 A:middle
in the bottom part of my script.

00:13:04.066 --> 00:13:07.526 A:middle
Now, if you also are the
type of person that relies

00:13:07.526 --> 00:13:09.586 A:middle
on third-party scripting
additions

00:13:09.586 --> 00:13:13.956 A:middle
to provide a missing command
like especially something

00:13:13.956 --> 00:13:17.596 A:middle
with text handling, you're
going to like libraries.

00:13:18.236 --> 00:13:21.936 A:middle
And if you just want to
simplify your scripts,

00:13:22.416 --> 00:13:24.276 A:middle
you're going to like libraries.

00:13:25.286 --> 00:13:29.336 A:middle
Now, it started for me by having
a routine that I like to use,

00:13:29.336 --> 00:13:33.496 A:middle
and then I started using
it in multiple scripts.

00:13:34.156 --> 00:13:36.186 A:middle
And it was quite useful.

00:13:36.186 --> 00:13:38.796 A:middle
I would just copy this
thing from, like a clipping.

00:13:38.796 --> 00:13:39.906 A:middle
I would paste in.

00:13:40.236 --> 00:13:42.436 A:middle
Then I found another
routine that I used,

00:13:42.436 --> 00:13:45.826 A:middle
and then I would paste that into
some of the scripts that I had.

00:13:46.216 --> 00:13:48.806 A:middle
But then I started changing
some of the routines

00:13:48.806 --> 00:13:51.836 A:middle
and then I added new ones and
then it just became this thing

00:13:51.836 --> 00:13:56.186 A:middle
of I couldn't keep track of all
the different stuff that I had.

00:13:57.036 --> 00:14:01.366 A:middle
So new in Mavericks we're
introducing AppleScript

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:13:57.036 --> 00:14:01.366 A:middle
So new in Mavericks we're
introducing AppleScript

00:14:01.366 --> 00:14:04.306 A:middle
libraries that will
help address this issue.

00:14:04.906 --> 00:14:08.016 A:middle
And what they are is a
new plug-in architecture

00:14:08.016 --> 00:14:13.276 A:middle
for AppleScript that allows you
to create your own libraries

00:14:13.726 --> 00:14:19.716 A:middle
of commands and gives you
quick and easy access to them

00:14:19.716 --> 00:14:21.766 A:middle
without having to go
through a bunch of --

00:14:22.296 --> 00:14:24.636 A:middle
of hoo-ha to get
to your handlers.

00:14:25.276 --> 00:14:26.906 A:middle
Now, they're different

00:14:26.906 --> 00:14:29.326 A:middle
than scripting editions
in a couple ways.

00:14:29.436 --> 00:14:31.796 A:middle
First of all, you can
write them in AppleScript.

00:14:32.276 --> 00:14:34.946 A:middle
You don't have to write
these in C or C++.

00:14:34.946 --> 00:14:36.476 A:middle
You can write them
in AppleScript.

00:14:37.126 --> 00:14:42.066 A:middle
And they're controlled by the
script that's calling them,

00:14:42.396 --> 00:14:45.726 A:middle
so that manages your
script libraries.

00:14:46.196 --> 00:14:49.076 A:middle
It means that the
library is only loaded

00:14:49.076 --> 00:14:52.616 A:middle
and it's only available when
your script tells it to load.

00:14:52.666 --> 00:14:55.966 A:middle
And it helps avoid
terminology conflicts that way.

00:14:56.226 --> 00:14:58.206 A:middle
It helps deal with resources.

00:14:58.496 --> 00:15:00.936 A:middle
And the script library
commands are run

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:14:58.496 --> 00:15:00.936 A:middle
And the script library
commands are run

00:15:00.936 --> 00:15:03.656 A:middle
by the process that's
executing the script.

00:15:04.386 --> 00:15:08.006 A:middle
So it's a lot smoother
to deal with.

00:15:08.516 --> 00:15:11.366 A:middle
In addition, these
libraries can take advantage

00:15:11.366 --> 00:15:15.586 A:middle
of AppleScript Objective-C,
so the wealth

00:15:15.586 --> 00:15:20.006 A:middle
of the Cocoa frameworks
and all of those classes

00:15:20.006 --> 00:15:24.336 A:middle
and methods now come into
play in the libraries

00:15:24.336 --> 00:15:25.686 A:middle
that you write yourself.

00:15:25.686 --> 00:15:29.496 A:middle
You can use some AppleScript
Objective-C and talk

00:15:29.576 --> 00:15:34.546 A:middle
to the NS string class and use
some of its methods as well.

00:15:35.656 --> 00:15:40.876 A:middle
In addition, your libraries can
contain their own terminology.

00:15:41.006 --> 00:15:43.786 A:middle
They can publish
their own terminology.

00:15:44.656 --> 00:15:47.746 A:middle
So you can make custom terms

00:15:47.746 --> 00:15:51.026 A:middle
that represent the
complex handlers

00:15:51.026 --> 00:15:52.846 A:middle
that are parts of your library.

00:15:53.316 --> 00:15:54.936 A:middle
Yes. It's really, really nice.

00:15:54.936 --> 00:15:58.366 A:middle
So, instead of remembering a
handler name, I can just put

00:15:58.366 --> 00:16:01.086 A:middle
in some terminology and
it will work perfectly.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:15:58.366 --> 00:16:01.086 A:middle
in some terminology and
it will work perfectly.

00:16:02.006 --> 00:16:05.536 A:middle
Now, in support of that, we've
created two new constructs.

00:16:06.036 --> 00:16:07.156 A:middle
The first is something

00:16:07.156 --> 00:16:09.926 A:middle
that we're calling a
script library reference.

00:16:10.056 --> 00:16:13.226 A:middle
And what it does is it
does a couple of functions.

00:16:13.226 --> 00:16:16.756 A:middle
It locates the script
library for you automatically

00:16:17.166 --> 00:16:20.166 A:middle
and prepares it for loading
and use in your script.

00:16:20.856 --> 00:16:23.116 A:middle
The second is something
brand new.

00:16:23.116 --> 00:16:27.316 A:middle
It's called a use clause,
and it is really a command

00:16:27.316 --> 00:16:29.266 A:middle
for importing terminology

00:16:29.466 --> 00:16:32.476 A:middle
and making it globally
available in your script.

00:16:33.236 --> 00:16:34.266 A:middle
Very powerful.

00:16:34.566 --> 00:16:36.096 A:middle
A lot of fun to use.

00:16:36.366 --> 00:16:37.596 A:middle
Let's take a look at this.

00:16:38.356 --> 00:16:43.486 A:middle
So, in its simplest
form, simplest form,

00:16:43.486 --> 00:16:48.646 A:middle
an AppleScript library can
just be in AppleScript routine

00:16:48.936 --> 00:16:51.746 A:middle
that you have like this
simple routine here

00:16:51.746 --> 00:16:55.086 A:middle
for converting the
case of some text

00:16:55.086 --> 00:16:56.966 A:middle
from uppercase to lowercase.

00:16:57.466 --> 00:17:01.126 A:middle
You can have this very
simple AppleScript handler

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:16:57.466 --> 00:17:01.126 A:middle
You can have this very
simple AppleScript handler

00:17:01.126 --> 00:17:02.146 A:middle
that you've created.

00:17:02.676 --> 00:17:06.006 A:middle
You take that, you
place it into a script.

00:17:07.185 --> 00:17:08.796 A:middle
Then you compile it.

00:17:09.925 --> 00:17:11.165 A:middle
You save it.

00:17:11.266 --> 00:17:13.886 A:middle
And, in this case, you just
save it as a script file.

00:17:15.455 --> 00:17:18.965 A:middle
Next, in your home
library folder,

00:17:19.705 --> 00:17:23.096 A:middle
you create a new folder
called script libraries

00:17:23.955 --> 00:17:25.906 A:middle
and then drag your script file,

00:17:26.306 --> 00:17:29.206 A:middle
your new script library,
into that folder.

00:17:30.446 --> 00:17:33.216 A:middle
Now you've installed it
into the script library,

00:17:33.216 --> 00:17:34.756 A:middle
AppleScript library system.

00:17:35.016 --> 00:17:36.046 A:middle
That's all you have to do.

00:17:36.046 --> 00:17:42.126 A:middle
So, to use it, it's just a
matter of typing the word

00:17:42.126 --> 00:17:46.156 A:middle
"script" followed by the
name of your library.

00:17:46.496 --> 00:17:49.526 A:middle
And you don't have to
use .scbt or anything,

00:17:49.736 --> 00:17:51.486 A:middle
just the name of your library.

00:17:52.526 --> 00:17:54.636 A:middle
And, when you compile this,

00:17:54.826 --> 00:17:58.376 A:middle
it becomes a script
library identifier.

00:17:58.716 --> 00:18:04.936 A:middle
That is now a representation
of your script library.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:17:58.716 --> 00:18:04.936 A:middle
That is now a representation
of your script library.

00:18:05.556 --> 00:18:08.926 A:middle
The AppleScript architecture
automatically located it

00:18:08.926 --> 00:18:10.926 A:middle
in the script libraries folder.

00:18:10.926 --> 00:18:13.006 A:middle
It's prepared it,
ready for load.

00:18:13.246 --> 00:18:16.106 A:middle
And now that it's an identifier,

00:18:16.646 --> 00:18:21.346 A:middle
you can target it using a
tell verb or a tell block

00:18:21.346 --> 00:18:24.626 A:middle
like this example where
I will be calling one

00:18:24.626 --> 00:18:26.946 A:middle
of the subroutines or
one of the handlers

00:18:26.946 --> 00:18:30.876 A:middle
within that library
script, pass it some text --

00:18:30.876 --> 00:18:34.916 A:middle
how now brown cow -- and
use a numeric indicator

00:18:34.916 --> 00:18:36.946 A:middle
to indicate I want uppercase.

00:18:37.456 --> 00:18:40.836 A:middle
So when this gets run,
the library is loaded,

00:18:40.836 --> 00:18:42.736 A:middle
the information is passed,

00:18:43.056 --> 00:18:45.576 A:middle
and the results come back
to you automatically.

00:18:46.886 --> 00:18:50.276 A:middle
Very simple way to
make a library.

00:18:50.276 --> 00:18:52.896 A:middle
Just very functional
but easy to do,

00:18:52.896 --> 00:18:55.586 A:middle
easy to install,
and easy to use.

00:18:56.586 --> 00:18:59.706 A:middle
Now, in its more advanced forms,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:19:00.036 --> 00:19:03.426 A:middle
a library can have
its own terminology.

00:19:03.576 --> 00:19:06.026 A:middle
And here is the dictionary
window

00:19:06.466 --> 00:19:08.936 A:middle
for an AppleScript library.

00:19:09.486 --> 00:19:13.746 A:middle
It has a single suite, and the
suite is called AppleScript

00:19:13.806 --> 00:19:15.006 A:middle
Text Utilities.

00:19:15.416 --> 00:19:20.626 A:middle
This suite has two commands
in it: one for changing,

00:19:20.626 --> 00:19:23.256 A:middle
transforming text; one
for replacing text.

00:19:23.786 --> 00:19:27.866 A:middle
It has a definition for the
suite and shows the definition

00:19:27.866 --> 00:19:30.966 A:middle
for each one of the
individual commands.

00:19:31.606 --> 00:19:34.366 A:middle
So in an advanced
form of a library,

00:19:34.626 --> 00:19:39.426 A:middle
you can have this
terminology available for you

00:19:39.426 --> 00:19:42.906 A:middle
and for your customers and
for everybody else to use.

00:19:43.656 --> 00:19:48.656 A:middle
So no longer are you calling
a handler name or having

00:19:48.656 --> 00:19:50.146 A:middle
to remember a handler name.

00:19:50.486 --> 00:19:55.026 A:middle
Instead, you can now use
terminology like transform text,

00:19:55.246 --> 00:19:58.126 A:middle
how now brown cow to uppercase.

00:19:58.736 --> 00:20:02.016 A:middle
And this will function
exactly the same way

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:19:58.736 --> 00:20:02.016 A:middle
And this will function
exactly the same way

00:20:02.266 --> 00:20:04.156 A:middle
as a library did before.

00:20:04.826 --> 00:20:07.126 A:middle
Now, that's in the
more advanced format.

00:20:07.926 --> 00:20:12.056 A:middle
So here's an example
script talking

00:20:12.056 --> 00:20:14.016 A:middle
to the Finder application,

00:20:14.326 --> 00:20:18.306 A:middle
and this contains a
tell block addressing an

00:20:18.306 --> 00:20:19.956 A:middle
AppleScript library.

00:20:20.586 --> 00:20:22.176 A:middle
You can see it right
there where it's going

00:20:22.176 --> 00:20:28.316 A:middle
to basically take the name
of some selected folders

00:20:28.316 --> 00:20:30.816 A:middle
in the Finder, and it's
going to iterate all

00:20:30.816 --> 00:20:33.716 A:middle
of these folders getting
their lowercase names

00:20:33.716 --> 00:20:35.756 A:middle
and converting them
to uppercase names.

00:20:36.166 --> 00:20:38.506 A:middle
So that's the purpose
of the script.

00:20:39.326 --> 00:20:44.926 A:middle
Now, you'll notice that, by
having an individual tell block

00:20:44.926 --> 00:20:48.666 A:middle
for every time I want to talk to
this library, in a small script

00:20:48.666 --> 00:20:51.416 A:middle
like that, I can
get away with it.

00:20:51.416 --> 00:20:55.516 A:middle
But, in a larger script where
you repeatedly might go back

00:20:55.516 --> 00:20:57.006 A:middle
and refer to this library,

00:20:57.186 --> 00:20:59.046 A:middle
that's a little clunky
to deal with.

00:20:59.926 --> 00:21:03.496 A:middle
In addition, there's
another issue going on here.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:20:59.926 --> 00:21:03.496 A:middle
In addition, there's
another issue going on here.

00:21:03.566 --> 00:21:06.386 A:middle
You'll notice that there
is a variable called

00:21:06.386 --> 00:21:08.636 A:middle
"adjusted name" that's
actually going

00:21:08.636 --> 00:21:13.206 A:middle
to store the transformation
result, hold it for a second

00:21:13.206 --> 00:21:17.886 A:middle
because it was within a tell
block, and then use it later

00:21:17.886 --> 00:21:21.686 A:middle
on in the script for the
Finder to assign the name

00:21:21.686 --> 00:21:25.416 A:middle
of the selected item to
that transformed name.

00:21:25.416 --> 00:21:27.566 A:middle
So you're doing this
little dance

00:21:27.566 --> 00:21:29.006 A:middle
because of this tell block.

00:21:29.526 --> 00:21:31.936 A:middle
And, again, this makes
it a little clunkier.

00:21:32.146 --> 00:21:36.396 A:middle
It works, but it's
not smooth syntax.

00:21:36.896 --> 00:21:40.256 A:middle
So we've come up with
something to address this issue.

00:21:40.946 --> 00:21:43.256 A:middle
And I'm just going to make
a little room at the top

00:21:43.256 --> 00:21:46.246 A:middle
of the script, and were going
to insert something new.

00:21:46.426 --> 00:21:48.596 A:middle
It's called a use clause.

00:21:49.266 --> 00:21:52.646 A:middle
And this use clause is
an importing command

00:21:53.236 --> 00:21:56.466 A:middle
that says "Use this library."

00:21:56.466 --> 00:21:58.766 A:middle
There's a script
library identifier.

00:21:59.116 --> 00:22:03.136 A:middle
And that means it will take it,
load it, and make its resources

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:21:59.116 --> 00:22:03.136 A:middle
And that means it will take it,
load it, and make its resources

00:22:03.136 --> 00:22:06.856 A:middle
and handlers available
for the script globally.

00:22:07.326 --> 00:22:10.876 A:middle
So, because I have a use
clause here, I don't need

00:22:10.876 --> 00:22:16.066 A:middle
to have the tell block around my
statement that calls my library.

00:22:16.066 --> 00:22:17.206 A:middle
I can remove that.

00:22:17.796 --> 00:22:21.336 A:middle
And I can also deal with
that little back and forth

00:22:21.336 --> 00:22:24.786 A:middle
about having you create a
variable to store the contents

00:22:24.786 --> 00:22:28.546 A:middle
of the command and then reapply
it and instead put everything

00:22:28.546 --> 00:22:32.386 A:middle
on one line so that the
Finder can say "Set the name

00:22:32.386 --> 00:22:36.166 A:middle
of the selected file to the
results of this transformation."

00:22:36.576 --> 00:22:40.666 A:middle
And then it just becomes one
seamless, transparent line.

00:22:41.546 --> 00:22:45.666 A:middle
So we can go from
this little clunkiness

00:22:46.016 --> 00:22:51.496 A:middle
to a very smooth example with
this new use clause ability.

00:22:51.956 --> 00:22:55.306 A:middle
And it works the same
way as anything else.

00:22:55.616 --> 00:22:57.186 A:middle
It works totally smooth.

00:22:57.186 --> 00:22:58.276 A:middle
It's transparent.

00:22:59.246 --> 00:23:02.166 A:middle
Now, let's talk about the
use clause for just a second.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:22:59.246 --> 00:23:02.166 A:middle
Now, let's talk about the
use clause for just a second.

00:23:02.586 --> 00:23:06.256 A:middle
It's about importing
terminology, and it allows you

00:23:06.306 --> 00:23:08.186 A:middle
to import the terminology

00:23:08.186 --> 00:23:11.606 A:middle
of script libraries
and applications.

00:23:12.496 --> 00:23:14.996 A:middle
So the importing commands,

00:23:14.996 --> 00:23:18.956 A:middle
when you import an
applications terminology

00:23:18.956 --> 00:23:20.696 A:middle
or a script libraries
terminology,

00:23:21.066 --> 00:23:23.636 A:middle
they are available
globally through the script.

00:23:23.636 --> 00:23:25.366 A:middle
You no longer have to address

00:23:25.366 --> 00:23:27.276 A:middle
that application
or that library.

00:23:27.526 --> 00:23:28.856 A:middle
It's not necessary.

00:23:29.716 --> 00:23:36.536 A:middle
And you can also use this use
-- use clause to specify the use

00:23:36.576 --> 00:23:39.176 A:middle
of a particular version
of AppleScript

00:23:39.456 --> 00:23:41.756 A:middle
or a particular version
of an application

00:23:41.756 --> 00:23:45.466 A:middle
or even a particular
version of a script library.

00:23:45.886 --> 00:23:48.086 A:middle
And it sure does make --

00:23:48.086 --> 00:23:51.186 A:middle
streamline the script
syntax that you have.

00:23:51.366 --> 00:23:55.816 A:middle
It makes things easier to
see, conceive, and use.

00:23:56.496 --> 00:24:00.636 A:middle
So here to show you the
use clause is my friend,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:23:56.496 --> 00:24:00.636 A:middle
So here to show you the
use clause is my friend,

00:24:00.636 --> 00:24:01.246 A:middle
Chris Nebel.

00:24:02.216 --> 00:24:02.536 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Chris Nebel: Okay.

00:24:02.856 --> 00:24:05.116 A:middle
I personally am really
excited about this feature.

00:24:05.116 --> 00:24:07.236 A:middle
This is, like, my favorite
AppleScript feature

00:24:07.236 --> 00:24:08.186 A:middle
in a long time.

00:24:08.186 --> 00:24:09.526 A:middle
It's one of those ones

00:24:09.526 --> 00:24:11.806 A:middle
that makes you wonder why
it didn't always work this

00:24:11.806 --> 00:24:12.056 A:middle
way [laughter].

00:24:13.666 --> 00:24:17.666 A:middle
So let's see how it
affects an actual script.

00:24:17.666 --> 00:24:22.686 A:middle
So I am the team mom --
that's the actual job title --

00:24:22.996 --> 00:24:24.566 A:middle
for my neighborhood soccer team.

00:24:24.696 --> 00:24:27.126 A:middle
Basically, it's handle all
the administrative stuff

00:24:27.126 --> 00:24:29.666 A:middle
so the coach doesn't have to.

00:24:29.826 --> 00:24:32.906 A:middle
And part of the job is
forwarding email around.

00:24:33.226 --> 00:24:36.706 A:middle
Someone -- someone on the
team sends me an email.

00:24:36.706 --> 00:24:38.286 A:middle
I have to send it out to
the rest of the group.

00:24:38.746 --> 00:24:40.246 A:middle
But the rules are
a little tricky.

00:24:40.506 --> 00:24:43.046 A:middle
I want to send it to everyone
else in the group except

00:24:43.046 --> 00:24:44.136 A:middle
for the original sender.

00:24:44.136 --> 00:24:46.476 A:middle
Them, I want to Cc.

00:24:46.476 --> 00:24:50.176 A:middle
And mail can almost
do this but not quite.

00:24:50.176 --> 00:24:54.206 A:middle
If you put an address book or
contacts group in the To field,

00:24:54.206 --> 00:24:56.056 A:middle
it can expand it out
to all the people.

00:24:56.386 --> 00:24:58.436 A:middle
But then it's up to me to
actually find the right person

00:24:58.436 --> 00:24:59.836 A:middle
and pull them over
to the Cc group.

00:24:59.836 --> 00:25:02.066 A:middle
It gets a bit out of -- it
gets a bit messy after a while,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:24:59.836 --> 00:25:02.066 A:middle
It gets a bit out of -- it
gets a bit messy after a while,

00:25:02.066 --> 00:25:03.536 A:middle
especially when you have
to do ten of these a day.

00:25:04.536 --> 00:25:07.306 A:middle
So -- but, automation, one
of the things it's for is

00:25:07.466 --> 00:25:09.956 A:middle
for filling in the gaps when the
system almost does what you want

00:25:10.186 --> 00:25:10.796 A:middle
but not quite.

00:25:10.796 --> 00:25:15.256 A:middle
So here's the script that I
wrote to handle this for me.

00:25:15.836 --> 00:25:19.736 A:middle
So we tell application mail get
the current selected message;

00:25:21.006 --> 00:25:22.066 A:middle
forward that message.

00:25:22.066 --> 00:25:25.776 A:middle
It creates a new forwarding
message ready to be filled in.

00:25:25.976 --> 00:25:28.136 A:middle
And then we flip
over to Contacts.

00:25:28.336 --> 00:25:30.526 A:middle
I have a group defined
Neighborhood Team so --

00:25:30.526 --> 00:25:34.306 A:middle
with every person in that group,
filled out an email address

00:25:34.306 --> 00:25:37.396 A:middle
for them, and then we flip
back to application mail.

00:25:38.716 --> 00:25:43.386 A:middle
And, if the sender of the
original message contains

00:25:43.386 --> 00:25:46.606 A:middle
that name, then we want to
add them as a Cc recipient;

00:25:47.056 --> 00:25:49.076 A:middle
otherwise, it's a To recipient.

00:25:50.746 --> 00:25:52.306 A:middle
And this works well enough.

00:25:52.466 --> 00:25:53.716 A:middle
Let's see it in action.

00:25:54.326 --> 00:25:59.906 A:middle
And the message was
originally from John.

00:25:59.906 --> 00:26:00.816 A:middle
He's been Cc'd.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:25:59.906 --> 00:26:00.816 A:middle
He's been Cc'd.

00:26:00.996 --> 00:26:02.686 A:middle
Everyone else, it goes "To."

00:26:03.296 --> 00:26:07.466 A:middle
So, obviously, the script works.

00:26:07.466 --> 00:26:13.106 A:middle
But you notice the sort
of back and forth tell --

00:26:13.106 --> 00:26:17.206 A:middle
tell this, tell this, tell
that, tell this, tell that.

00:26:17.646 --> 00:26:20.196 A:middle
And that's very typical of
any script when you're talking

00:26:20.196 --> 00:26:21.416 A:middle
to more than one application.

00:26:21.416 --> 00:26:23.246 A:middle
You have to flip back and
forth between them a lot.

00:26:24.446 --> 00:26:27.606 A:middle
So wouldn't it be nice if the --

00:26:27.606 --> 00:26:28.796 A:middle
if AppleScript could figure

00:26:28.796 --> 00:26:31.136 A:middle
out which application you're
actually talking to just

00:26:31.136 --> 00:26:32.436 A:middle
by the terms that you're using.

00:26:32.876 --> 00:26:34.476 A:middle
Well, that's pretty
much what use does.

00:26:34.476 --> 00:26:36.256 A:middle
Let's look at how
the script changes.

00:26:39.076 --> 00:26:42.836 A:middle
So two use statements
at the top.

00:26:43.166 --> 00:26:44.716 A:middle
The first one is
application mail,

00:26:45.056 --> 00:26:47.256 A:middle
and I'm also defining
a shorthand name

00:26:47.256 --> 00:26:48.616 A:middle
for it that I can use later.

00:26:48.746 --> 00:26:51.436 A:middle
It's essentially a property
whose value is application mail.

00:26:51.546 --> 00:26:54.136 A:middle
I'm also going to use
application contacts.

00:26:55.236 --> 00:26:56.646 A:middle
The first line is
pretty much the same.

00:26:56.886 --> 00:26:58.546 A:middle
Get the selection of mail.

00:26:58.546 --> 00:27:00.396 A:middle
I have to specify that
it's mail selection

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:26:58.546 --> 00:27:00.396 A:middle
I have to specify that
it's mail selection

00:27:00.396 --> 00:27:02.096 A:middle
because contacts
has a selection to.

00:27:02.096 --> 00:27:03.476 A:middle
So got to be explicit there.

00:27:04.026 --> 00:27:07.056 A:middle
But then we can forward
the message.

00:27:07.056 --> 00:27:08.476 A:middle
And notice there's
no tell block here.

00:27:08.776 --> 00:27:13.206 A:middle
The compiler knows that,
forward, mail is the only thing

00:27:13.206 --> 00:27:16.096 A:middle
that defined forward; so
it will send that to mail.

00:27:16.616 --> 00:27:20.246 A:middle
And then we repeat with
every person in a group.

00:27:20.676 --> 00:27:22.566 A:middle
No tell blocks again
because it knows that person

00:27:22.566 --> 00:27:24.746 A:middle
in group are defined by
contacts and not by mail.

00:27:25.306 --> 00:27:29.706 A:middle
You're building up the
mail address if the sender

00:27:29.706 --> 00:27:31.976 A:middle
of the original message were
actually getting this straight

00:27:31.976 --> 00:27:34.036 A:middle
from mail instead
of prefetching it,

00:27:34.856 --> 00:27:37.816 A:middle
and this actually
comes from contacts.

00:27:37.816 --> 00:27:42.946 A:middle
We're mixing two applications
in the same statement making you

00:27:42.946 --> 00:27:44.556 A:middle
to Cc or To recipient.

00:27:44.556 --> 00:27:46.706 A:middle
And, again, there's no
tell blocks anywhere here.

00:27:47.236 --> 00:27:52.596 A:middle
And, yet, it works
exactly the same.

00:27:53.516 --> 00:27:58.546 A:middle
[ Pause ]

00:27:59.046 --> 00:28:02.466 A:middle
So, essentially, what use
does is it lets you get rid

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:27:59.046 --> 00:28:02.466 A:middle
So, essentially, what use
does is it lets you get rid

00:28:02.466 --> 00:28:04.996 A:middle
of all the bookkeeping that
the computer really ought

00:28:04.996 --> 00:28:06.276 A:middle
to be able to do for you.

00:28:06.846 --> 00:28:10.266 A:middle
Notice that this script, this
new script, is much narrower

00:28:10.836 --> 00:28:11.686 A:middle
than the original one.

00:28:12.916 --> 00:28:14.596 A:middle
It gets rid of all
the tell blocks

00:28:14.806 --> 00:28:18.746 A:middle
so you can concentrate just
on your application logic

00:28:18.906 --> 00:28:21.026 A:middle
and not have to worry
so much about exactly

00:28:21.066 --> 00:28:22.806 A:middle
which application
you're telling to do what

00:28:23.186 --> 00:28:25.826 A:middle
because AppleScript should
be able to do that for you.

00:28:26.016 --> 00:28:28.426 A:middle
Now it can.

00:28:29.516 --> 00:28:34.656 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:28:35.156 --> 00:28:35.396 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Sal Soghoian: Yeah.

00:28:35.396 --> 00:28:38.136 A:middle
It's going to take me
a while to wrap my head

00:28:38.136 --> 00:28:41.816 A:middle
around all the different places
I can use the use clause,

00:28:42.436 --> 00:28:45.886 A:middle
but I'm very excited by
it because I've been able

00:28:45.886 --> 00:28:48.026 A:middle
to do some really
interesting things

00:28:48.026 --> 00:28:50.076 A:middle
in a single line statement

00:28:50.306 --> 00:28:53.246 A:middle
that it would usually
take me multiple lines

00:28:53.246 --> 00:28:55.026 A:middle
and multiple tell blocks to do.

00:28:55.516 --> 00:28:58.456 A:middle
It's a very powerful
construct and especially

00:28:58.456 --> 00:28:59.846 A:middle
when it's used with libraries.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:29:00.036 --> 00:29:00.666 A:middle
It's great.

00:29:01.786 --> 00:29:05.536 A:middle
So, AppleScript libraries, they
are a new plug-in architecture

00:29:05.536 --> 00:29:08.626 A:middle
that allows you to get at
your favorite handlers.

00:29:08.866 --> 00:29:10.606 A:middle
You can create these yourself.

00:29:11.166 --> 00:29:13.376 A:middle
They're different than
scripting additions

00:29:13.476 --> 00:29:15.466 A:middle
because you can write
them in AppleScript

00:29:16.576 --> 00:29:19.436 A:middle
and that the script
manages their use

00:29:19.526 --> 00:29:22.166 A:middle
and use of resources as well.

00:29:22.756 --> 00:29:25.896 A:middle
They can also have access
to AppleScript Objective-C,

00:29:25.896 --> 00:29:29.566 A:middle
so that means the
world of Cocoa, methods

00:29:29.746 --> 00:29:31.886 A:middle
and classes are at
your disposal.

00:29:32.686 --> 00:29:36.676 A:middle
And you can publish your own
terminology for them as well.

00:29:36.986 --> 00:29:41.076 A:middle
In support, we've added the new
script library reference and,

00:29:41.076 --> 00:29:44.276 A:middle
as we just demonstrated,
the new use clause

00:29:44.486 --> 00:29:47.076 A:middle
to help automatically
find, locate,

00:29:47.076 --> 00:29:49.256 A:middle
and load these things
globally for you.

00:29:50.216 --> 00:29:55.406 A:middle
Now, we have a session this
afternoon on just libraries

00:29:55.406 --> 00:29:59.026 A:middle
where we get into
detail and show you how

00:29:59.026 --> 00:30:03.416 A:middle
to construct a library, not
only a simple one but one

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:29:59.026 --> 00:30:03.416 A:middle
to construct a library, not
only a simple one but one

00:30:03.416 --> 00:30:07.786 A:middle
in AppleScript Objective-C, one
that actually has a terminology.

00:30:07.786 --> 00:30:10.816 A:middle
And, for the first time
anywhere in the world,

00:30:11.046 --> 00:30:16.116 A:middle
we will show you how to write
a scripting dictionary file

00:30:16.276 --> 00:30:17.316 A:middle
or an sdef [laughter].

00:30:19.516 --> 00:30:22.556 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:30:23.056 --> 00:30:24.066 A:middle
It is sick, sick, sick.

00:30:24.426 --> 00:30:25.416 A:middle
You can't miss it.

00:30:25.806 --> 00:30:27.536 A:middle
So that's this afternoon.

00:30:27.536 --> 00:30:29.116 A:middle
It's right in this same room.

00:30:29.116 --> 00:30:32.146 A:middle
It session 416 at 3:15 pm.

00:30:32.456 --> 00:30:35.916 A:middle
If this is interesting you, I
suggest please come to this.

00:30:35.916 --> 00:30:38.366 A:middle
When you're done, you'll
really understand them

00:30:38.556 --> 00:30:40.396 A:middle
and be able to start
using these.

00:30:40.396 --> 00:30:41.446 A:middle
They're very powerful.

00:30:42.876 --> 00:30:45.376 A:middle
Next we're going to talk
about notifications.

00:30:45.756 --> 00:30:47.776 A:middle
Informing the user
of what's going on.

00:30:48.266 --> 00:30:50.806 A:middle
So the other day I
was reading this blog

00:30:50.806 --> 00:30:53.416 A:middle
about how they got
it right in OS X

00:30:53.416 --> 00:30:54.976 A:middle
with the Notification Center.

00:30:54.976 --> 00:30:56.666 A:middle
And the guy says, "Yeah, man.

00:30:56.916 --> 00:31:00.536 A:middle
You know, they -- they're
located in a central location.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:30:56.916 --> 00:31:00.536 A:middle
You know, they -- they're
located in a central location.

00:31:00.536 --> 00:31:03.416 A:middle
They're organized
by application.

00:31:03.816 --> 00:31:06.406 A:middle
And they disappear quickly

00:31:06.406 --> 00:31:09.856 A:middle
so that there is no
clutter on your screen.

00:31:10.046 --> 00:31:12.196 A:middle
It's really nice
that they're there.

00:31:12.436 --> 00:31:16.406 A:middle
And it can even provide a
mechanism for you to respond.

00:31:16.556 --> 00:31:18.566 A:middle
And, in the new version
that you've seen,

00:31:18.986 --> 00:31:21.706 A:middle
you can even have replies
and stuff like that.

00:31:22.346 --> 00:31:24.806 A:middle
And, you know, they're
designed not

00:31:24.806 --> 00:31:27.046 A:middle
to annoy you or get in the way.

00:31:27.946 --> 00:31:31.186 A:middle
[Laughter] And they should
never, ever leap, jump,

00:31:31.186 --> 00:31:34.846 A:middle
or hop and definitely
not bounce."

00:31:35.456 --> 00:31:39.806 A:middle
So I'm showing you this
because, for many, many years,

00:31:39.806 --> 00:31:45.136 A:middle
this is the way that scripts
tried to notify you until now.

00:31:45.976 --> 00:31:48.806 A:middle
So we've added notifications
support

00:31:48.806 --> 00:31:50.786 A:middle
in Automator and AppleScript.

00:31:51.256 --> 00:31:53.316 A:middle
And we've integrated
it [applause] -- yes.

00:31:55.706 --> 00:32:00.026 A:middle
And we've integrated it in
both applications and --

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:31:55.706 --> 00:32:00.026 A:middle
And we've integrated it in
both applications and --

00:32:00.476 --> 00:32:04.916 A:middle
so that there's no more need
for these mobile dialogs

00:32:04.916 --> 00:32:06.656 A:middle
that just kind of hang around,

00:32:06.926 --> 00:32:09.126 A:middle
and you can now create
your automations

00:32:09.126 --> 00:32:11.496 A:middle
that are 100 percent
bounce-free [laughter].

00:32:13.486 --> 00:32:15.406 A:middle
So let's take a look
at how this works.

00:32:15.876 --> 00:32:19.336 A:middle
There's a Notifications Control
-- System Preference pane,

00:32:19.336 --> 00:32:20.896 A:middle
right, in the Master
Preference pane.

00:32:20.896 --> 00:32:25.466 A:middle
If you open that in Mavericks,
you'll see that your favorite,

00:32:25.466 --> 00:32:30.666 A:middle
you know, automation applets
and droplets appear in the list

00:32:30.666 --> 00:32:33.176 A:middle
of applications like
everything else.

00:32:33.266 --> 00:32:36.666 A:middle
And you can select them
and set their preferences.

00:32:36.666 --> 00:32:40.406 A:middle
For example, I can select my
photo droplet, and I can choose

00:32:40.466 --> 00:32:42.676 A:middle
that it will display
as an alert.

00:32:43.096 --> 00:32:45.546 A:middle
Or I can even say, No; I
don't want any display.

00:32:45.546 --> 00:32:46.786 A:middle
Just use the sound.

00:32:47.476 --> 00:32:50.246 A:middle
Or, if I have something
that I use quite a lot

00:32:50.736 --> 00:32:53.036 A:middle
and doesn't require
a notification,

00:32:53.276 --> 00:32:55.176 A:middle
then I can just turn
it off and take it

00:32:55.176 --> 00:32:59.036 A:middle
out of the Notification system
by just clicking that checkbox.

00:32:59.826 --> 00:33:04.626 A:middle
So, when it comes to Automator,
many people don't know that,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:32:59.826 --> 00:33:04.626 A:middle
So, when it comes to Automator,
many people don't know that,

00:33:04.626 --> 00:33:08.616 A:middle
when you run an Automator
workflow or applet,

00:33:09.146 --> 00:33:11.036 A:middle
it does provide some feedback.

00:33:11.366 --> 00:33:14.096 A:middle
And you'll notice
at the very top

00:33:14.246 --> 00:33:16.856 A:middle
of your menu bar there's a gear.

00:33:17.256 --> 00:33:20.736 A:middle
And, if you've ever seen that
or even caught your eye with it,

00:33:20.876 --> 00:33:25.166 A:middle
if you click on that, it will
show you every workflow that's

00:33:25.166 --> 00:33:27.276 A:middle
running and generally
give you an idea

00:33:27.276 --> 00:33:29.096 A:middle
about where the workflow is.

00:33:29.516 --> 00:33:31.886 A:middle
But you have to hold
the cursor down.

00:33:32.166 --> 00:33:34.756 A:middle
And, if you're still holding,
you might get this notice

00:33:34.756 --> 00:33:36.326 A:middle
that says the workflow ended.

00:33:37.266 --> 00:33:41.026 A:middle
But most people don't know
about that and so, generally,

00:33:41.026 --> 00:33:43.346 A:middle
the way that you know
that a workflow is --

00:33:43.756 --> 00:33:45.636 A:middle
is finished is nothing.

00:33:45.636 --> 00:33:47.566 A:middle
There's nothing there
to show you.

00:33:48.476 --> 00:33:52.246 A:middle
Now, with the Automator
in Mavericks,

00:33:52.316 --> 00:33:55.376 A:middle
we've introduced a new
notification action,

00:33:56.156 --> 00:33:58.976 A:middle
and this will cause a
notification to occur.

00:33:59.616 --> 00:34:02.896 A:middle
And you can insert
it more than once

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:33:59.616 --> 00:34:02.896 A:middle
And you can insert
it more than once

00:34:02.896 --> 00:34:04.326 A:middle
in your workflow if you want.

00:34:04.326 --> 00:34:05.326 A:middle
You could put it into the start.

00:34:05.326 --> 00:34:07.476 A:middle
You could put it in key
points in the workflow.

00:34:07.696 --> 00:34:09.136 A:middle
You could just put
it at the end.

00:34:09.136 --> 00:34:10.606 A:middle
Whatever works for you.

00:34:11.426 --> 00:34:14.906 A:middle
And, in addition, it provides
various options for which one

00:34:14.906 --> 00:34:16.596 A:middle
of the fields you want to do,

00:34:16.596 --> 00:34:20.326 A:middle
and it also supports Automator
variables, workflow variables.

00:34:20.706 --> 00:34:22.976 A:middle
So we can have dynamic
information

00:34:22.976 --> 00:34:26.646 A:middle
in that dialog related to
the workflow that was run.

00:34:28.275 --> 00:34:32.446 A:middle
Now, why would you need this
kind of thing in a workflow?

00:34:32.536 --> 00:34:36.266 A:middle
Well, here's a workflow that
I use myself for home movies,

00:34:36.266 --> 00:34:38.396 A:middle
and it's a video
compressing workflow.

00:34:38.646 --> 00:34:43.456 A:middle
Anytime I shoot a bunch of
stuff on my iPhone or a camera,

00:34:44.065 --> 00:34:47.025 A:middle
I take the raw files and I
run it through this droplet.

00:34:47.025 --> 00:34:48.786 A:middle
And let me just walk you
through it real quick.

00:34:49.136 --> 00:34:51.906 A:middle
So it's an applet,
so you can see

00:34:51.906 --> 00:34:55.076 A:middle
at the top it says it receives
whatever you drop onto it.

00:34:55.426 --> 00:34:58.176 A:middle
And then the first
action, I have a find --

00:34:58.236 --> 00:35:01.736 A:middle
filter finder items, so it
looks just for movie files.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:34:58.236 --> 00:35:01.736 A:middle
filter finder items, so it
looks just for movie files.

00:35:01.736 --> 00:35:04.096 A:middle
In case something else
gets accidentally dropped

00:35:04.096 --> 00:35:05.306 A:middle
on it, it ignores it.

00:35:05.906 --> 00:35:10.086 A:middle
Then, the next action is
creating a workflow variable

00:35:10.086 --> 00:35:14.256 A:middle
that stores the references
to the raw movie files.

00:35:14.776 --> 00:35:18.396 A:middle
Then I proceed to do the first
encoding at a lower thing

00:35:18.396 --> 00:35:21.836 A:middle
of 480p to a certain
location on my drive.

00:35:22.796 --> 00:35:28.046 A:middle
Next, I append a -480p
to the end of the name

00:35:28.046 --> 00:35:30.856 A:middle
of all the created
video files so I know

00:35:30.856 --> 00:35:32.716 A:middle
which ones are the
lower resolution.

00:35:33.606 --> 00:35:35.376 A:middle
Then I use a workflow variable.

00:35:35.376 --> 00:35:37.466 A:middle
I call back that
workflow variable.

00:35:37.466 --> 00:35:41.046 A:middle
I get the original list
of source references.

00:35:41.396 --> 00:35:47.176 A:middle
I perform another encoding pass
using 720p or 1080p depending

00:35:47.176 --> 00:35:50.316 A:middle
on where I'm going to,
to a certain location.

00:35:50.726 --> 00:35:53.486 A:middle
And then again I append
to the end of the name.

00:35:54.066 --> 00:35:58.006 A:middle
So this workflow can take
quite a while to run.

00:35:58.006 --> 00:36:02.586 A:middle
If you drag four or five
10GB files onto this,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:35:58.006 --> 00:36:02.586 A:middle
If you drag four or five
10GB files onto this,

00:36:02.806 --> 00:36:06.656 A:middle
it can go on for quite a while,
and you have no idea of knowing

00:36:06.656 --> 00:36:08.506 A:middle
where you are in this process.

00:36:08.556 --> 00:36:11.646 A:middle
So this is an example of a
workflow that you would want

00:36:11.646 --> 00:36:13.246 A:middle
to add a notification to.

00:36:13.826 --> 00:36:15.536 A:middle
And to do that it's pretty easy.

00:36:15.536 --> 00:36:17.666 A:middle
You just open up
your library view.

00:36:17.956 --> 00:36:20.966 A:middle
You search in the Search
field for notification.

00:36:21.386 --> 00:36:23.876 A:middle
And you'll see that
it appears in the list

00:36:23.876 --> 00:36:26.066 A:middle
of available Automator actions.

00:36:26.326 --> 00:36:28.326 A:middle
Hit the Return key;
it becomes selected.

00:36:28.326 --> 00:36:30.736 A:middle
You can see the display
of information

00:36:30.736 --> 00:36:32.706 A:middle
about the new notification
action.

00:36:32.996 --> 00:36:36.456 A:middle
Hit the Return key again and it
will automatically inserted it

00:36:36.456 --> 00:36:38.286 A:middle
into the bottom of my workflow.

00:36:38.696 --> 00:36:40.576 A:middle
Then it's just a
matter of me filling

00:36:40.576 --> 00:36:43.676 A:middle
out the fields the
way I want, saving it.

00:36:44.056 --> 00:36:47.746 A:middle
So now I drag my video
file on top of that.

00:36:47.746 --> 00:36:51.806 A:middle
And I hit the gear, but
after a period of time,

00:36:52.556 --> 00:36:55.386 A:middle
the first encoding thing
appears on my desktop.

00:36:55.806 --> 00:36:57.666 A:middle
Then some more time goes by,

00:36:58.156 --> 00:37:01.176 A:middle
and the second encoded
file appears along

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:36:58.156 --> 00:37:01.176 A:middle
and the second encoded
file appears along

00:37:01.176 --> 00:37:02.536 A:middle
with a notification.

00:37:02.956 --> 00:37:05.676 A:middle
So now I know what's
been processed.

00:37:05.676 --> 00:37:09.426 A:middle
If I come back from eating my
doughnut or lunch, whatever,

00:37:09.656 --> 00:37:12.116 A:middle
and I just look at the
machine, I can say, "Oh, great.

00:37:12.116 --> 00:37:13.406 A:middle
The encoding went fine.

00:37:13.636 --> 00:37:15.966 A:middle
Okay. I'm ready to do the
next batch or something."

00:37:16.426 --> 00:37:19.646 A:middle
And because the parameters
are settable

00:37:19.646 --> 00:37:22.806 A:middle
in the System Preference
pane, I can choose to have

00:37:22.806 --> 00:37:27.386 A:middle
that be an alert that demands
that I close that alert so just

00:37:27.386 --> 00:37:29.026 A:middle
as a confirmation as well.

00:37:30.166 --> 00:37:34.546 A:middle
Now, for AppleScript, what we
did is we added a new command

00:37:34.546 --> 00:37:36.996 A:middle
that's part of the
standard editions,

00:37:37.386 --> 00:37:40.586 A:middle
and it's called Display
Notification, of course.

00:37:41.246 --> 00:37:43.116 A:middle
And here's the verb.

00:37:43.386 --> 00:37:46.336 A:middle
There's an optional
parameter with title.

00:37:46.336 --> 00:37:51.206 A:middle
There's another optional
parameter here for subtitle.

00:37:51.626 --> 00:37:54.216 A:middle
And you can put the
name of the sound file

00:37:54.216 --> 00:37:55.676 A:middle
that you want to have play.

00:37:55.776 --> 00:37:58.166 A:middle
Now, all those are
optional parameters,

00:37:58.166 --> 00:37:59.706 A:middle
but you have to use one of them.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:38:00.286 --> 00:38:02.656 A:middle
And it creates a notification.

00:38:03.356 --> 00:38:06.316 A:middle
So, in that example
I sent to Trudy,

00:38:06.576 --> 00:38:09.846 A:middle
this is basically
the repeat routine.

00:38:10.106 --> 00:38:13.056 A:middle
I would just open some
space here after the repeat,

00:38:13.336 --> 00:38:16.956 A:middle
insert that into there so now
there's display notification.

00:38:17.306 --> 00:38:21.566 A:middle
And I can add custom data
like the number of items

00:38:21.566 --> 00:38:25.216 A:middle
that were processed into
the final message so that,

00:38:25.216 --> 00:38:27.206 A:middle
when I drag a bunch of images

00:38:27.206 --> 00:38:30.696 A:middle
onto the photo droplet,
it processes.

00:38:30.786 --> 00:38:33.906 A:middle
And, then, after a while, it
will display the notification

00:38:33.906 --> 00:38:35.356 A:middle
with the custom information.

00:38:35.836 --> 00:38:37.356 A:middle
It's that simple to use.

00:38:37.806 --> 00:38:40.436 A:middle
So here to show you
notifications

00:38:40.436 --> 00:38:42.216 A:middle
in action is Chris Nebel.

00:38:42.476 --> 00:38:42.816 A:middle
Thank you.

