Next I'd like to talk about
accessibility integration.

00:45:17.676 --> 00:45:21.706 A:middle
Now, some of you might be
familiar with Speakable Items.

00:45:21.706 --> 00:45:24.026 A:middle
How many people in here
have used Speakable Items?

00:45:25.446 --> 00:45:26.286 A:middle
Quite a few.

00:45:26.366 --> 00:45:27.076 A:middle
Quite a few.

00:45:27.546 --> 00:45:32.726 A:middle
And it's an architecture
built into OS X

00:45:33.556 --> 00:45:38.356 A:middle
in the accessibility frameworks
and allows you to speak commands

00:45:38.356 --> 00:45:40.796 A:middle
to your computer and have
them perform them for you.

00:45:41.476 --> 00:45:43.186 A:middle
And it has a lot of integration.

00:45:43.186 --> 00:45:45.286 A:middle
There is a lot of
customization built

00:45:45.286 --> 00:45:47.196 A:middle
into the standard
set of commands.

00:45:47.196 --> 00:45:49.846 A:middle
For example, you can
say, Mail this to mom,

00:45:49.846 --> 00:45:52.116 A:middle
and it will understand
who mom is.

00:45:52.566 --> 00:45:54.776 A:middle
You could say meet with
Karl Whelan [phonetic],

00:45:55.016 --> 00:45:58.616 A:middle
and it will look up Karl
Whelan in your address book

00:45:58.616 --> 00:46:02.626 A:middle
and then create a new
meeting for you in Calendar.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:45:58.616 --> 00:46:02.626 A:middle
and then create a new
meeting for you in Calendar.

00:46:03.146 --> 00:46:05.666 A:middle
It has a lot of other commands
that are just basically,

00:46:05.666 --> 00:46:08.286 A:middle
you know, work things
like open iPhoto,

00:46:08.286 --> 00:46:10.836 A:middle
bring this window forward,
that kind of stuff.

00:46:10.896 --> 00:46:12.106 A:middle
But it's very useful.

00:46:12.106 --> 00:46:16.546 A:middle
So a lot of people use
this who are not involved

00:46:16.546 --> 00:46:17.726 A:middle
in accessibility issues.

00:46:17.726 --> 00:46:20.266 A:middle
It's just a nice
power feature to have.

00:46:21.056 --> 00:46:27.216 A:middle
So what we've done in Mavericks
is we've created a new entity

00:46:27.216 --> 00:46:29.076 A:middle
called Speakable Workflows.

00:46:29.076 --> 00:46:31.756 A:middle
It's a way of saving
your workflows

00:46:32.196 --> 00:46:36.716 A:middle
into the Speakable Items'
architecture and have it work

00:46:36.716 --> 00:46:37.976 A:middle
for you automatically.

00:46:37.976 --> 00:46:41.646 A:middle
So you can extend a set of
commands that are available

00:46:41.646 --> 00:46:43.636 A:middle
by voice using Automator.

00:46:44.386 --> 00:46:46.376 A:middle
And this is how it works.

00:46:46.376 --> 00:46:49.056 A:middle
So, to turn on Speakable Items,

00:46:49.096 --> 00:46:52.616 A:middle
you just go to the
Accessibility Preference pane.

00:46:52.916 --> 00:46:54.776 A:middle
At the bottom of the list

00:46:54.776 --> 00:46:58.366 A:middle
of different accessibility
features is Speakable Items.

00:46:58.596 --> 00:47:01.206 A:middle
You select that and then
just click the radio button

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:46:58.596 --> 00:47:01.206 A:middle
You select that and then
just click the radio button

00:47:01.206 --> 00:47:01.996 A:middle
to turn it on.

00:47:02.746 --> 00:47:05.986 A:middle
As confirmation, you'll see
this floating round window.

00:47:05.986 --> 00:47:08.116 A:middle
That's the Speech
Feedback window.

00:47:08.426 --> 00:47:11.756 A:middle
When that's available,
the computer is ready

00:47:11.756 --> 00:47:13.496 A:middle
to respond to your commands.

00:47:13.946 --> 00:47:16.746 A:middle
And, by default, you just
press down the Escape key

00:47:16.746 --> 00:47:19.226 A:middle
and say your command and it
will start working for you.

00:47:20.156 --> 00:47:24.546 A:middle
Now, in Automator, if you want
to create a Speakable Workflow,

00:47:24.546 --> 00:47:26.066 A:middle
I have an example here.

00:47:26.686 --> 00:47:30.536 A:middle
So I use USB keys all the time.

00:47:30.536 --> 00:47:31.226 A:middle
I have one here.

00:47:31.226 --> 00:47:32.946 A:middle
I call it Digital Briefcase.

00:47:33.546 --> 00:47:36.726 A:middle
And, you know, I'm constantly
plugging them into the computer,

00:47:36.726 --> 00:47:38.356 A:middle
and then I have to
go eject them.

00:47:38.616 --> 00:47:41.676 A:middle
So I have to find some dialog,
whether it's an open dialog

00:47:41.676 --> 00:47:44.506 A:middle
or finder window, find the
stupid little down thing,

00:47:44.506 --> 00:47:46.476 A:middle
click that, and then
wait for the thing

00:47:46.476 --> 00:47:47.736 A:middle
to eject and then grab it.

00:47:48.076 --> 00:47:51.136 A:middle
I would really like to just
be able to tell the computer

00:47:51.136 --> 00:47:53.386 A:middle
"Eject Digital Briefcase"
and, plop,

00:47:53.386 --> 00:47:55.016 A:middle
it will just pull it out for me.

00:47:55.416 --> 00:47:58.776 A:middle
So this is the workflow that
does that, and I'll walk you

00:47:58.776 --> 00:48:00.496 A:middle
through it to show
you how to do this.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:47:58.776 --> 00:48:00.496 A:middle
through it to show
you how to do this.

00:48:01.256 --> 00:48:04.616 A:middle
So it's an applet by default,

00:48:05.296 --> 00:48:10.176 A:middle
and the first action is a
Find Finder Items action,

00:48:10.556 --> 00:48:12.496 A:middle
and it looks for two parameters.

00:48:12.496 --> 00:48:17.286 A:middle
One, it looks for volume whose
name is Digital Briefcase.

00:48:17.996 --> 00:48:21.006 A:middle
Once it finds that
volume, it will pass

00:48:21.006 --> 00:48:24.936 A:middle
that to the next action which
is just simply Eject Disc,

00:48:25.066 --> 00:48:27.056 A:middle
and it will eject
for us automatically.

00:48:27.936 --> 00:48:32.856 A:middle
Then the next step is to specify
some text I want as a response.

00:48:33.436 --> 00:48:35.676 A:middle
And I type the word Done!

00:48:35.926 --> 00:48:40.556 A:middle
and then have that
spoken by a certain voice.

00:48:40.736 --> 00:48:42.076 A:middle
I've chosen Samantha.

00:48:42.746 --> 00:48:46.396 A:middle
So then I choose to
save this workflow.

00:48:46.396 --> 00:48:48.146 A:middle
This will be my Speakable
Workflow.

00:48:48.396 --> 00:48:52.996 A:middle
And in the Save sheet you'll see
that there is a File Format menu

00:48:53.496 --> 00:48:54.776 A:middle
that says Application.

00:48:55.286 --> 00:49:00.326 A:middle
Well, if I click on that,
there's a new file format.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:48:55.286 --> 00:49:00.326 A:middle
Well, if I click on that,
there's a new file format.

00:49:00.516 --> 00:49:03.696 A:middle
If you have Speakable Items
architecture turned on

00:49:03.696 --> 00:49:08.326 A:middle
and installed on your machine,
you will see this in Automator

00:49:08.326 --> 00:49:10.096 A:middle
and it's called a
Speakable Item.

00:49:10.696 --> 00:49:14.056 A:middle
So, therefore, I can save
this as a Speakable Item.

00:49:14.626 --> 00:49:16.886 A:middle
You'll notice that
Speakable Item appears

00:49:16.936 --> 00:49:18.636 A:middle
on the File Format menu,

00:49:18.906 --> 00:49:22.636 A:middle
but it also automatically
locates the Speakable Items

00:49:22.636 --> 00:49:25.576 A:middle
folder which is within
your Speech folder which is

00:49:25.616 --> 00:49:26.876 A:middle
within your Home folder.

00:49:27.546 --> 00:49:29.906 A:middle
In other words, that's
the location

00:49:30.196 --> 00:49:32.276 A:middle
that the speech architecture
uses.

00:49:32.636 --> 00:49:36.606 A:middle
So, when you save,
you want to save it

00:49:36.606 --> 00:49:40.116 A:middle
with a name being the
name of the command.

00:49:40.116 --> 00:49:43.696 A:middle
So, in this case, I'm going to
say Eject Digital Briefcase,

00:49:43.896 --> 00:49:46.196 A:middle
and that's what I want to be
able to say to my computer.

00:49:46.596 --> 00:49:47.536 A:middle
I save that.

00:49:47.536 --> 00:49:52.106 A:middle
It will install it into the
Speakable Items architecture

00:49:52.106 --> 00:49:53.316 A:middle
for me automatically.

00:49:53.886 --> 00:49:58.246 A:middle
So the next time my thumb drive
is plugged into the computer

00:49:58.246 --> 00:50:02.956 A:middle
like it is here, if I want to,
no matter what program I'm in,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:49:58.246 --> 00:50:02.956 A:middle
like it is here, if I want to,
no matter what program I'm in,

00:50:03.286 --> 00:50:06.516 A:middle
if I want to eject
it, I just simply --

00:50:07.156 --> 00:50:10.296 A:middle
I just simply say the command -

00:50:11.426 --> 00:50:13.626 A:middle
&gt;&gt; "Eject Digital
Briefcase" [laughter].

00:50:13.986 --> 00:50:18.206 A:middle
&gt;&gt; It does it.

00:50:18.316 --> 00:50:18.676 A:middle
&gt;&gt; "Done!"

00:50:19.246 --> 00:50:20.296 A:middle
&gt;&gt; -- and then says done.

00:50:21.466 --> 00:50:26.886 A:middle
So there's a very simple example
of how you can take workflows

00:50:26.886 --> 00:50:31.996 A:middle
and integrate them in with the
speech recognition architecture

00:50:31.996 --> 00:50:35.286 A:middle
in the operating system
to perform custom actions.

00:50:35.966 --> 00:50:40.736 A:middle
Now, in preparation for release
of Mavericks in the fall,

00:50:41.056 --> 00:50:45.796 A:middle
we'll be posting a new website
called Speakable Workflows.com

00:50:46.146 --> 00:50:49.576 A:middle
that will have hundreds of
examples that you can download.

00:50:50.046 --> 00:50:52.656 A:middle
In addition, they'll be a
feedback mechanism there

00:50:52.656 --> 00:50:56.416 A:middle
that you can send us response
about how you use this,

00:50:56.516 --> 00:50:59.216 A:middle
the kind of things that you're
looking for, that kind of thing.

00:50:59.216 --> 00:51:02.636 A:middle
So we encourage you to give
this a try in Mavericks.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:50:59.216 --> 00:51:02.636 A:middle
So we encourage you to give
this a try in Mavericks.

00:51:03.666 --> 00:51:08.186 A:middle
So, in summary, this has been
a great release for automation.

00:51:08.556 --> 00:51:10.546 A:middle
We've had a lot of
new stuff happening.

00:51:10.546 --> 00:51:13.346 A:middle
Specifically, we
added iCloud support

00:51:13.416 --> 00:51:16.336 A:middle
so that you can have your
scripts just distributed

00:51:16.336 --> 00:51:19.086 A:middle
across all the computers
that you use.

00:51:19.486 --> 00:51:23.556 A:middle
We added code signing so that
you can distribute your applets

00:51:23.556 --> 00:51:27.226 A:middle
and droplets to every -- to your
customers or to your friends

00:51:27.526 --> 00:51:30.716 A:middle
without invoking any of
the Gatekeeper responses.

00:51:31.206 --> 00:51:35.066 A:middle
We now have a new construct
for extending the power

00:51:35.066 --> 00:51:38.146 A:middle
of AppleScript through
AppleScript libraries

00:51:38.626 --> 00:51:43.306 A:middle
which you can write yourself in
AppleScript and expose commands

00:51:43.306 --> 00:51:46.456 A:middle
and terminology that you
didn't have available before.

00:51:47.396 --> 00:51:50.506 A:middle
And we now have introduced
the new use clause

00:51:50.506 --> 00:51:54.256 A:middle
that will really streamline
the syntax of your scripts

00:51:54.256 --> 00:51:57.016 A:middle
and add a lot of power
and ability to them.

00:51:58.166 --> 00:52:01.666 A:middle
And we've implemented
notification support in addition

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:51:58.166 --> 00:52:01.666 A:middle
And we've implemented
notification support in addition

00:52:01.666 --> 00:52:03.796 A:middle
to our new Speakable Workflows.

00:52:04.346 --> 00:52:07.586 A:middle
So that's quite a bit that's
been going on this year.

00:52:07.586 --> 00:52:09.476 A:middle
This is a great release for us.

00:52:09.476 --> 00:52:10.996 A:middle
We're really excited about it.

